  "Experiment": "The experimental design unfolds in four phases. Phase 1: Behavioral Annotation Collection. Using the ACACE platform, we collect pairwise comparison data from 120 annotators across three NLP tasks—CSQA, ABSA, and NLI—including cognitive metrics (response latency, mouse dynamics, optional eye-tracking). Each annotator evaluates 150 explanation pairs generated by baseline models (T5-Explain, CPACE, C3LPGCN). We also record post-comparison confidence ratings and optional verbal retrospection. Phase 2: Cognitive Reward Modeling. We train an IRL-based reward model using a transformer architecture that takes as input the textual explanation pair and outputs a scalar reward estimate. Features include semantic similarity (via BERTScore), syntactic complexity, concept coverage (using ConceptNet), and behavioral traces (e.g., long response times indicating difficulty). The model is trained to recover the latent reward function that best explains observed human choices and cognitive load indicators. Phase 3: RL-Based Generator Fine-Tuning. We initialize a contrastive explanation generator (e.g., Flan-T5-XXL) and fine-tune it using Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO), with the learned cognitive reward as the objective. Baselines include MLE-trained generators and those optimized on task accuracy alone. Phase 4: Closed-Loop Evaluation & Transfer. We deploy the improved generator to produce new explanations, which are re-evaluated via ACACE. We measure progression in reward score, inter-annotator agreement, and downstream impact on user trust (via simulated agent interaction studies). We also test zero-shot transfer to a new domain (e.g., financial QA) using Explanation Distillation Trees. Success is defined by: (1) >25% increase in average cognitive reward, (2) higher correlation with expert judgment than static metrics, and (3) reduced need for human annotation over cycles due to effective synthetic preference modeling.",
